WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
So we have a hypothetical situation where we have discovered this chick weight dataset

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:16.240
that exists built into R, it's one of the built-in datasets.

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:24.040
So we have chick weight, it's got weight, time, chick, diet, and maybe we've made some

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:31.320
plots with that stuff, so we look at chick weight over time, nice line plot, maybe we've

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:39.139
looked at the density, and we say I want to build a Shiny app with this, I've got these

00:00:39.139 --> 00:00:46.520
nice plots and I want to put them in a Shiny app, but I'm dreading that aspect of going

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:55.880
in and setting up that whole UI, because that's just code that I haven't written before,

00:00:55.880 --> 00:00:57.400
it's annoying to remember how to write it.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:03.119
So that is a kind of a use case that the UI Editor is attempting to make a lot easier.

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:11.040
So we can go in, in this project that we have that's empty, except for these chickplots.r

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:15.360
script that has those plots, you know, we load the Shiny UI Editor, and then we say

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:20.680
launch editor, and we give it this application, we call it chick-plots, and you notice we

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:26.040
don't actually have chick-plots in here, and what it's going to do is recognize that doesn't

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:31.000
exist yet, and ask you a few questions about creating it, so you say, you know, I want

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.279
to start a new app from a template, you choose which template, right now we don't have that

00:01:37.279 --> 00:01:42.599
many, so we're going to do a single file template that is the Geyser app, run that, and now

00:01:42.839 --> 00:01:48.879
the UI Editor is up and running, and it's running just this simple Geyser app, just

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:54.400
with two plots instead of the typical one, but it's an app that you are well familiar

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:55.400
with.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:02:00.000
So we can actually go in, we see now that there is chick-plots in here, we can click

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.320
into that, and we see an app.r, and we can open that up, and this is the code that the

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:13.279
UI Editor is currently running, and so we can see that if we want to change stuff, like

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:20.240
say we have our header here, and it is spanning the whole top, we drag it over here, it updates,

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:25.479
and we see now the header is only spanning the first column there, and so any update

00:02:25.479 --> 00:02:32.559
that you make in the UI Editor is automatically updated in the app code itself.

00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:39.119
So that's nice, but what if you wanted to actually adjust what is being plotted?

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:44.240
A lot of the fun stuff in Shiny apps is doing the plots, and so we already have render plots

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:50.039
here for this disk plot and blue plot, and so what we can do is take some of our chick-plot

00:02:50.039 --> 00:03:01.839
data, and grab this code, and replace in our app.r this disk plot with that code, and

00:03:01.839 --> 00:03:07.399
we can save it, and you'll see that there's an error, we can check this, it says, okay,

00:03:07.399 --> 00:03:17.160
could not find function ggplot, so we actually need to load ggplot, so say library ggplot2,

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:26.600
save that, another error, object chick not found, so let's go back in here one more time,

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:33.240
filter, oh, this is a classic error, filter is one of those functions that exists in dplyr

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:42.839
and also in the base, so we need to actually explicitly load dplyr, and now we've been

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:47.960
making these changes directly to our server, looking at the errors that are coming through

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:53.720
in the UI editor, and now we actually have that plot up and running in our app, and so one of

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.679
the things, we probably want to change this to not be disk plot, so we're going to call this,

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:06.119
you know, weights, so we've updated, now it's not there, because it's looking for the plot output

00:04:06.119 --> 00:04:10.520
of weights, which we don't have, because we haven't renamed it, go in here, rename it to weights,

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:16.760
save it, and it's back, and so we can continue doing this for a bunch of different things,

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:22.600
so let's go take this distribution plot here, and let's replace the blue plot with that,

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:34.279
blue plot, that paste in there, save it, there, there, a little bit confusingly called blue plot,

00:04:34.279 --> 00:04:39.640
even though we have some orange red distributions, so let's do the same thing here,

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:48.040
call this distributions, or maybe call it dist, once again, it's gone, let's go fix it,

00:04:50.839 --> 00:04:57.480
save it, it's back, so you can see that we can just continue to make our changes here,

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:07.559
let's call this chick weights, and code is continuing to update, so one thing that we

00:05:07.559 --> 00:05:12.519
might want to do also is, we have this number of bins slider, which isn't doing anything for us

00:05:12.519 --> 00:05:18.519
right now, but we do have, we're filtering to a given number of chicks, in this case it's six,

00:05:19.239 --> 00:05:24.040
so what we might want to do is take this slider and repurpose it to decide that

00:05:24.839 --> 00:05:32.200
filtered number for us, so let's change it to num chicks, call it,

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:43.399
chicks to plot, and I don't think we have that many, let's maybe set the min to one, max to,

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:50.600
and start at a value that is reasonable, say five,

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:57.000
and let's set a step value, so we don't have incremental, let's say step value of one,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:03.000
so we can go in here, we see that we actually have this slider up and running, but it's not

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.920
hooked up to anything, but we now know that we have created an input id of num chicks,

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:16.440
so we can just copy that, come over here, say input, input, dollar sign, num chicks,

00:06:17.239 --> 00:06:22.839
place that, copy this, get rid of that, because we don't need it anymore, save,

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:34.920
so in theory this will now change, but the classic factor problem is getting us, so

00:06:36.119 --> 00:06:42.119
it's not exactly doing what we want, because we're doing chick less than input number of chicks,

00:06:43.079 --> 00:06:47.160
it's not actually giving us the same value, and this is actually happening before we did this,

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:53.320
it's just we didn't notice it, because we didn't count the lines, so we should go into chick weight,

00:06:53.959 --> 00:07:03.959
and we'll do mutate, chick equals as.numeric, as well as the si integer,

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:15.720
and that might be right, there we go, now it's all fixed, but we can do all of that,

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:20.760
you know, we can mess with our code, we can update our plots, and all we have to do is just

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:29.000
go back and forth between the ui editor and the code, and so the idea is you don't have to sit

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.320
there and fiddle with this, you know, grid card, what's the argument name, how do I, you know,

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:37.959
where do I nest this, I want to put it over here, yeah, you don't need to worry about that,

00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:46.359
you can just focus on writing good data science, you know, doing correct plots, you know, doing

00:07:46.359 --> 00:07:52.200
your dplyr pipes properly, we want you to focus on those issues which are straightforward, and not

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:59.399
this like, you know, crazy world that is how do you get your text to align properly in your ui,

00:07:59.399 --> 00:08:05.399
how do you make your header a little bit taller than it was before, that's stuff that doesn't

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:11.640
influence how good you are as a data scientist, so we're trying to make that as easy as possible,

00:08:12.279 --> 00:08:21.799
you know, before we talked about like if we had a table, right, so we have like this code here,

00:08:22.519 --> 00:08:28.920
so we'll take that out here and we use output

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:39.960
table

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:46.119
so

00:08:53.880 --> 00:09:00.119
you actually put that table in here

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:02.280
which

00:09:07.239 --> 00:09:11.159
so we go into this grid card that has nothing in it and we say

00:09:13.719 --> 00:09:18.280
gt and it's like gt output

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:32.280
so this idea of like, you know, we have a table in here, we want to make it bigger so we can

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:40.359
see the table, we have this table in here, but the ui editor doesn't support, doesn't have,

00:09:40.359 --> 00:09:45.080
you know, doesn't know about gt tables yet, and so what it does is it gives you this

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:51.880
little gray box that says, hey, I have this ui function that I don't know about, here's the code,

00:09:53.159 --> 00:09:57.880
you can't edit it because I don't know about it, but it is treated just like any other node,

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:04.359
so you could take this and put it up here, you know, and drag this down, it's not your tables in

00:10:04.359 --> 00:10:16.200
there, so you can like treat it just like you would any other node, but it doesn't know about

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:22.359
it, and so the idea there is that we don't limit, you know, if you have some, you know,

00:10:23.239 --> 00:10:30.599
cool custom function or just a function that's not included yet, it's not going to make it so

00:10:30.599 --> 00:10:35.960
you can't use the ui editor, it just means that you won't be able to use a nice ui editor

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:42.760
settings panel to change it, but you could still lay out your app and everything and place it where

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:50.280
you want within the app, and then see what it is, so I think that's, that will help, you know,

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:56.679
ideally in the future, every possible thing that you put in your Shiny app is known, but I don't

00:10:56.679 --> 00:11:03.479
think that's ever going to be the case, and so this is how that is treated on the editor, so

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:11.159
that's important to know.

